03602nam a22004215i 9781503622555DE-B159720220131112047.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220131t20221997cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97815036225557 a10.1515/97815036225552doi  a(DE-B1597)582181  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 7aLIT0040202bisacsh1 aCadava, Eduardo, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aEmerson and the Climates of History /cEduardo Cadava. 1aStanford, CA : bStanford University Press, c[2022] 4c©1997  a1 online resource (268 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tAcknowledgments -- tContents -- tAbbreviations -- tPreface: "We Cannot Write the Order of the Variable Winds" -- tChapter One. The Climates of History -- tChapter Two. Nature's Archives -- tChapter Three. The Rhetoric of Slavery and War -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThis book brings together a wide range of materials from history, religion, philosophy, horticulture, and meteorology to argue that Emerson articulates his conception of history through the language of the weather. Focusing on Emerson's persistent use of climatic and meteorological metaphors, the book demonstrates that Emerson's reflections on the weather are inseparable from his preoccupation with the central historical and political issues of his day. The author suggests that Emerson's writings may be read as both symptomatic and critical of the governing rhetorics through which Americans of his day thought about the most important contemporary issues, and that what has often been seen as Emerson's retreat from the arena of history into the domain of spirit is in fact an effort to re-treat or rethink the nature of history in terms of questions of representation. What distinguishes this book from the work of other critics who are reassessing Emerson's relation to history is its attempt to think through the way in which the figures of Emerson's rhetoric—figures (like frost, snow, the auroras, and nature in general) which often seem to have nothing to do with either history or politics—are themselves traversed by the conflictual histories of slavery, race, destiny, revolution, and the meaning of America. It differs, that is, in proposing a textual model for reading Emerson that measures his engagement with changing historical and political relations in terms of the way he works to revise the language he inherits. There can be no reading of Emerson, the author suggests, that does not trace the movement of his figures and tropes as they become something else, as they open onto questions of history.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 31. Jan 2022) 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / American / General.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978150362255540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781503622555423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781503622555/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles